1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,600
People were noticing, all throughout this time, that Forrestal seemed like he was unraveling.

2
00:00:06,660 --> 00:00:09,660
He started developing these weird, nervous tics.

3
00:00:10,260 --> 00:00:13,740
He said, I'm being followed by strange, foreign-looking men.

4
00:00:14,740 --> 00:00:20,040
He started dipping his fingers into glasses of water all the time and just wetting his lips.

5
00:00:20,280 --> 00:00:22,860
I drink only distilled water or rainwater.

6
00:00:23,500 --> 00:00:25,200
I'm glad to see what you're getting at.

7
00:00:25,460 --> 00:00:29,840
A couple of big, tough Navy guys grab him and throw him the hell out the window.

8
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:31,500
I'm absolutely convinced that's what happened.

9
00:00:34,420 --> 00:00:41,880
And in the 80s, it felt like maybe the U.S. moved from a strategy of secrecy and denial to flood the zone.

10
00:00:42,520 --> 00:00:45,120
And flood the zone doesn't mean put out BS.

11
00:00:45,340 --> 00:00:47,700
It means put out partial truths and put out a lot.

12
00:00:50,600 --> 00:00:56,960
People did see it emerge from the water, circled their transport ship twice, totally silent.

13
00:00:57,060 --> 00:00:58,140
He said there were high winds.

14
00:00:58,140 --> 00:01:00,000
This thing should have been bouncing around in the wind.

15
00:01:00,080 --> 00:01:01,180
It was rock solid.

16
00:01:02,180 --> 00:01:06,760
He writes in his diary at 3.30 a.m. on August 12, 1825.

17
00:01:07,340 --> 00:01:12,380
The Night Watch reported this orange spherical object rise from the ocean.

18
00:01:13,960 --> 00:01:15,980
Let's get down to the fundamental reality here.

19
00:01:16,060 --> 00:01:17,820
We are dealing with a phenomenon.

20
00:01:18,300 --> 00:01:18,600
Yes.

21
00:01:18,600 --> 00:01:22,580
It is a reality-shattering phenomenon.

22
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:27,820
I do believe that there's a good reason to think that we have been monitored or observed for a long time.

23
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,420
It's not that we're being too crazy and too fringe.

24
00:01:30,480 --> 00:01:32,900
We're not being, we're not going out there enough.

25
00:01:32,980 --> 00:01:33,820
I think that's right.

26
00:01:33,820 --> 00:01:45,760
Here with the great Richard Dolan, we just did this amazing kind of live show for a bunch of people.

27
00:01:45,940 --> 00:01:46,420
It was a lot of fun.

28
00:01:46,500 --> 00:01:47,420
It was a lot of fun.

29
00:01:47,420 --> 00:01:54,120
I told you afterwards, I think you're the easiest person to interview because I just have to tee you off and then you just go.

30
00:01:55,760 --> 00:01:56,900
It's an honor to be here.

31
00:01:57,020 --> 00:01:58,340
It's a long time coming for me.

32
00:01:58,340 --> 00:02:09,680
Maybe what we should start with here in this kind of private setting is I'm curious to know how you got into UFO research to begin with and who your inspirations are.

33
00:02:10,520 --> 00:02:13,820
Yeah, I have a lot of inspirations in my life, some in this field, some beyond.

34
00:02:15,140 --> 00:02:16,820
This is a story I've told a few times.

35
00:02:16,900 --> 00:02:21,520
I don't want to sound like I'm rehashing it, but I want to try to do it fresh.

36
00:02:21,520 --> 00:02:34,080
I was always a very driven young person and I always felt like there was this very intellectualized destiny that I wanted to pursue.

37
00:02:34,300 --> 00:02:35,340
I didn't really know what it would be.

38
00:02:35,680 --> 00:02:45,620
I've always been drawn to history and politics, discovered a real deep love of literature when I was in my early 20s and that's remained with me.

39
00:02:45,620 --> 00:02:52,840
But as a young person trying to make a professional life, I thought, well, I would finish a PhD in history and teach at a university.

40
00:02:53,540 --> 00:03:00,940
When I was in my youngest portion of that, I was totally unqualified to try to do what I ended up doing.

41
00:03:01,020 --> 00:03:02,260
I was studying German history.

42
00:03:03,060 --> 00:03:05,340
My German language was minimal at best.

43
00:03:05,340 --> 00:03:16,200
And here I was studying basically the J. Edgar Hoover of Otto von Bismarck's 19th century Germany back in the 1850s and 60s, a man named Wilhelm Stieber.

44
00:03:16,920 --> 00:03:18,340
And I'm like, oh, this is an interesting guy.

45
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:21,080
And I'm diving into his career and I thought, I'm going to do a dissertation on him.

46
00:03:21,620 --> 00:03:25,440
I wrote 150 pages or whatever and it failed.

47
00:03:25,440 --> 00:03:31,020
I was unable to crack Wilhelm Stieber.

48
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:31,820
He's an interesting guy.

49
00:03:31,980 --> 00:03:33,720
He blackmailed people.

50
00:03:33,720 --> 00:03:36,920
He created a brothel in Berlin in 1870.

51
00:03:37,100 --> 00:03:38,520
He would take pictures, all of his stuff.

52
00:03:38,600 --> 00:03:42,740
He literally was the J. Edgar Hoover of German unification.

53
00:03:43,100 --> 00:03:43,360
Absolutely.

54
00:03:43,580 --> 00:03:43,980
Interesting.

55
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:45,800
And it was amazing.

56
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:47,780
But anyway, so I bailed out of that.

57
00:03:49,660 --> 00:03:51,440
That was when the Berlin Wall came down.

58
00:03:51,540 --> 00:03:52,300
I was there.

59
00:03:52,400 --> 00:03:54,600
I was in Berlin during that whole period, 1989.

60
00:03:54,900 --> 00:03:57,720
I was trying to wrap this thing up and it just failed.

61
00:03:57,720 --> 00:04:03,460
So I go back to the States and I left for about two years.

62
00:04:03,860 --> 00:04:07,040
I was studying at the University of Rochester in upstate New York.

63
00:04:07,420 --> 00:04:09,840
And then I went back and I thought, you know what?

64
00:04:10,220 --> 00:04:11,460
My German sucked.

65
00:04:11,620 --> 00:04:13,360
So why don't I just do like American history?

66
00:04:13,460 --> 00:04:14,340
Because I know that language.

67
00:04:14,340 --> 00:04:18,280
And I went in and I focused on United States diplomatic history.

68
00:04:18,960 --> 00:04:19,780
And I did great.

69
00:04:19,860 --> 00:04:21,120
I was really, really into it.

70
00:04:21,480 --> 00:04:22,460
I was very deeply.

71
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:24,180
And by this time I was in my early 30s.

72
00:04:24,180 --> 00:04:25,140
So I was a bit more mature.

73
00:04:25,860 --> 00:04:29,860
And I was studying Harry Truman and his presidency.

74
00:04:29,860 --> 00:04:31,640
And I was doing a lot of Soviet stuff too.

75
00:04:31,640 --> 00:04:40,260
But I ended up studying 1950 national security strategy just before the outbreak of war in Korea.

76
00:04:41,280 --> 00:04:42,320
And, you know, I was like, who cares?

77
00:04:42,460 --> 00:04:43,920
But that was what I was doing at the time.

78
00:04:44,120 --> 00:04:51,080
And I wrote another 125, 150 pages of a dissertation on that, which I did not finish.

79
00:04:51,240 --> 00:04:52,760
So I had two unfinished dissertations.

80
00:04:53,880 --> 00:05:00,020
And I was in a bookstore, just like an ordinary bookstore one day in Syracuse, New York.

81
00:05:00,020 --> 00:05:04,820
And I saw a copy of Timothy Good's very classic work, Above Top Secret.

82
00:05:04,940 --> 00:05:05,240
Oh, yeah.

83
00:05:05,380 --> 00:05:07,760
And it was the subtitle of that book that caught my attention.

84
00:05:07,900 --> 00:05:09,780
It was the Worldwide UFO Cover-Up.

85
00:05:10,080 --> 00:05:10,720
Oh, wow.

86
00:05:11,380 --> 00:05:11,740
So here we are.

87
00:05:11,800 --> 00:05:12,820
It's like 1994.

88
00:05:13,600 --> 00:05:15,040
So I'm about 32 years old.

89
00:05:15,360 --> 00:05:18,420
And I flipped through the book.

90
00:05:18,480 --> 00:05:20,460
And I'm like, I know that name.

91
00:05:20,980 --> 00:05:21,980
I read his diaries.

92
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:23,360
I know that department.

93
00:05:23,600 --> 00:05:24,440
Wait, what?

94
00:05:24,920 --> 00:05:25,360
UFOs?

95
00:05:25,440 --> 00:05:26,220
What is this?

96
00:05:26,720 --> 00:05:29,480
Like it was this great cognitive dissonance.

97
00:05:30,060 --> 00:05:33,240
And I thought, this looks like a fairly serious book.

98
00:05:33,300 --> 00:05:34,460
He's got a variety of documents.

99
00:05:34,720 --> 00:05:37,320
It looks like his research is at least halfway decent.

100
00:05:39,120 --> 00:05:41,920
And my question wasn't, are UFOs real?

101
00:05:42,540 --> 00:05:45,320
My question wasn't like, are there abductions or are there crop circles?

102
00:05:45,640 --> 00:05:46,600
I wasn't down that road.

103
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:52,460
My question was simply, even if this was a mistake, like if they were mistakenly interested

104
00:05:52,460 --> 00:05:58,480
in this UFO thing back in, or the flying saucers back in the 40s, how come I never read about

105
00:05:58,480 --> 00:06:00,640
it in any academic history book, like ever?

106
00:06:01,360 --> 00:06:05,480
Even if it was a mistake, like would you not think that's kind of interesting?

107
00:06:05,480 --> 00:06:13,080
You go back to 1947, 48, and I'm reading here in Tim Good's book, like the Air Force and

108
00:06:13,080 --> 00:06:15,240
the Navy, like they were totally into this.

109
00:06:16,060 --> 00:06:18,460
And you're in the early Cold War.

110
00:06:18,640 --> 00:06:19,880
Yeah, that's damned interesting.

111
00:06:20,460 --> 00:06:24,000
And so I thought, well, I bought the book and I just went down that rabbit hole.

112
00:06:24,060 --> 00:06:26,500
And I thought, I'm going to just spend like two or three months.

113
00:06:26,500 --> 00:06:31,740
And I just want to resolve for myself, like, was this a thing or not a thing?

114
00:06:31,780 --> 00:06:32,260
And that was it.

115
00:06:32,300 --> 00:06:35,820
And then I figured like I would just leave and go on to my life.

116
00:06:36,300 --> 00:06:38,040
And those are my favorite, famous last words.

117
00:06:38,180 --> 00:06:42,420
So I read Tim's book and it was like, this is a very good book.

118
00:06:42,580 --> 00:06:46,420
Started going online, back with the baby internet as it existed.

119
00:06:46,520 --> 00:06:48,240
All the news groups, you suck.

120
00:06:48,320 --> 00:06:48,940
No, you suck.

121
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:49,760
I'm going to kill you.

122
00:06:50,020 --> 00:06:52,460
You know, the bulletin boards as they existed in the 90s.

123
00:06:52,460 --> 00:06:55,000
But there were some good UFO bulletin boards.

124
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:56,360
And I went down that.

125
00:06:57,020 --> 00:07:00,060
And the next thing I knew, I just, I left.

126
00:07:00,140 --> 00:07:01,840
I left the University of Rochester.

127
00:07:02,980 --> 00:07:09,680
And it was a real crisis in my life because I'm in my early 30s.

128
00:07:09,740 --> 00:07:10,880
I'm like, I've got all this ambition.

129
00:07:11,020 --> 00:07:11,940
I wanted to do something.

130
